Cryptocurrency exchanges serve as critical infrastructure within the blockchain ecosystem, providing traders with accessible platforms for exchanging cryptocurrencies across a vast blockchain network. Atomic swap represents a promising underlying protocol for currency exchanges, ensuring secure currency swaps for traders. However, most existing atomic swap solutions fail to consider user privacy, with only a few achieving privacy preservation under specific constraints (e.g., only supporting anonymous blockchains or relying on the stable price assumption). These constraints limit their applicability in the volatile cryptocurrency market. To remove these constraints, we present Pace, a novel privacy-preserving atomic swap protocol that supports public blockchains like Bitcoin and Ethereum. Pace also maintains the balance security of both honest platforms and traders while removing the stable price assumption, thereby enhancing its applicability in the volatile cryptocurrency market. To enhance user privacy, we propose a 1-to-1 swap protocol that integrates mixers as relays, ensuring all transfers within the swap achieve unlinkability. To avoid atomicity issues arising from an increase in transfers, we propose the combinable and randomizable puzzle, an extension of existing randomizable puzzles that enables atomic execution for multiple transfers with different puzzles. In addition, we extend 1-to-1 swap protocol to 1-to-n swap protocol to achieve flexible exchange rate settings, thereby removing the stable price assumption. We then provide a comprehensive security analysis to demonstrate that, even if the platform and another user are malicious, the unlinkability of the honest user’ cross-chain addresses is still guaranteed. Finally, we implement a prototype of Pace and validate its practicality.